    "abstract": "We present a privacy-preserving protocol to anonymously collect information about\na social graph.  The typical application of our protocol is Bluetooth-enabled ``contact-tracing apps''\nwhich record information about proximity between users to infer the risk of propagation\nof COVID-19 among them. The main contribution of this work is to enable a central\nserver to construct an anonymous graph of interactions between users. This graph\ngives the central authority insight on the propagation of the virus, and allows it\nto run predictive models on it while protecting the privacy of users. The main\ntechnical tool we use is an accumulator scheme due to Camenisch and\nLysyanskaya to keep track of the credentials of users,\nand prove accumulated credentials in Zero-Knowledge.",
    "keywords": [
      "Exposure notification",
      "contact tracing",
      "Zero-Knowledge proofs",
      "sigma-protocols",
      "Accumulators",
      "Signatures of Knowledge",
      "COVID-19."
    ],
    "category": "Applications",
